<paragraph id="6C6E430BFF9DFFC3FAB2AD708080FD2D" blockId="41.[151,1437,325,713]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">
<emphasis id="5EA59F19FF9DFFC3FAB2AD70815EFDDC" bold="true" box="[199,315,542,568]" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Remarks.</emphasis>
Previous records from the coast of 
<collectingRegion id="AE158DE9FF9DFFC3F8A0AD708322FDDC" box="[725,839,542,568]" country="Brazil" name="Sao Paulo" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">São Paulo</collectingRegion>
include Ubatuba, and São Sebastião (
<bibRefCitation id="08403EFAFF9DFFC3FE8DAD7080B1FDB8" author="Almeida, A. O. &amp; Anker, A. &amp; Mantelatto, F. L." pageId="41" pageNumber="42" pagination="110 - 120" refId="ref51914" refString="Almeida, A. O., Anker, A. &amp; Mantelatto, F. L. (2014) A new snapping species of the shrimp genus Typton Costa, 1844 (Decapoda: Palaemonidae) from the coast of Sao Paulo, southeastern Brazil. Zootaxa, 3835 (1), 110 - 120. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3835.1.6" type="journal article" year="2014">
Almeida 
<emphasis id="5EA59F19FF9DFFC3FF16AD7185F8FDDC" box="[1379,1437,542,568]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). It is found in association with sponges, including 
<taxonomicName id="ABD13888FF9DFFC3F955AD2C8173FD65" authority="(Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864)" baseAuthorityName="Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti" baseAuthorityYear="1864" class="Demospongiae" family="Mycalidae" genus="Mycale" kingdom="Animalia" order="Poecilosclerida" pageId="41" pageNumber="42" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="angulosa" subGenus="Zygomycale">
<emphasis id="5EA59F19FF9DFFC3F955AD2C8317FDB8" box="[800,882,578,604]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Mycale</emphasis>
(
<emphasis id="5EA59F19FF9DFFC3F9F1AD2C846EFDB8" box="[900,1035,578,604]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">Zygomycale</emphasis>
) 
<emphasis id="5EA59F19FF9DFFC3FE68AD2C84E1FDB8" box="[1053,1156,578,604]" italics="true" pageId="41" pageNumber="42">angulosa</emphasis>
(Duchassaing &amp; Michelotti, 1864)
</taxonomicName>
